Lessons that can be learned from the Cuban Crisis today
“Thirteen Days” („Dreizehn Tage“), a new film about the Cuban Crisis, will soon be released in cinemas of many countries.
Everyone should watch this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it offers insights into current events – particularly regarding controversies surrounding a US national missile defense system and various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy convened his closest advisors at the White House.
Air photographs had revealed the construction of a weapons station on Cuba.
The decisions made during the following thirteen days, and those that could not be avoided, could have led to the outbreak of an atomic war.
The film illustrates what happened at the White House during these days.
Tapes recorded during President Kennedy's presidency played a crucial role in the creation of the film.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard organized a discussion roundtable to discuss both the film and the crisis it addresses.
Participants in this roundtable included: Robert McNamara, Secretary of Defense under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a history professor at Harvard who wrote a book about the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a political science professor at Harvard who presented a classic study on the Cuban Crisis, "The Essence of Decision," thirty years ago.
Moreover, Peter A. Almond, the producer of the film, was present.
Although the filmic adaptation of the topic received criticism in various points, the participants in the discussion could agree that the film portrays the problems and the pressure President Kennedy was confronted with exactly as they were in reality.
What conclusions can be drawn today from the Cuban Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summed it up as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in case of a crisis, but ultimately it is only the president who bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisers—both civilian and military—wanted to attack Cuba at the time.
Only through Kennedy's冷静 analysis and his persistent questions could alternatives and dangers that were crucial to determining the consequences be shown.
It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; furthermore, communication lines must remain open.
Pushing an opponent into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open, which would allow for an understanding of the opponent's situation, could prove disastrous.
· The United States relies on allies.
Kennedy acted that way because NATO, other allies, and world opinion supported him.
· A certain period of time is needed for good decision-making.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to push him into action.
The fact that a week passed during which all involved factors were examined and weighed with great precision was crucial for the outcome.
But would such a timeframe for deliberation still exist today given the current mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it is necessary to put oneself in the opponent's shoes.
In one of the most criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade Kennedy imposed on Cuba was primarily meant to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's determination, not as a means to stop specific Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more calmly?
After all, the USA also stationed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba merely reflected this policy.
But Kennedy showed himself fearful concerning the consequences that the stationing of Soviet missiles in Cuba would have had for Berlin's defense.
The pressure of nuclear weapons on Cuba would have further endangered the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
Ultimately, "the Berlin Crisis was resolved through the outcomes of the Cuban Crisis," as historian Ernest May claimed.
"It will be too late soon," was a widely circulated argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba even while they believed the missiles were en route by sea towards Cuba.
An a force of approximately 180,000 U.S. troops was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a blitz bombing campaign that would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack on Kosovo sixty years later. "I needed thirty years," McNamara said, "to find out that there were already nuclear weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and 90 of them strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information during a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew about it."
And I explicitly recommended that atomic weapons be used.
I knew that this would have led to the destruction of Cuba."
Castro and, to a greater extent, his comrade Che Guevara were ready to let Cuba go up in smoke so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for world revolution!
An invasion could therefore have resulted in the deaths of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because Kennedy's administration lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (which often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is convinced that an invasion "would certainly have led" to a Soviet nuclear attack on the USA.
Khrushchev's control over the Soviet military on Cuba was limited: aircraft of the U2 type, which flew over Cuban airspace, were shot down despite explicit contrary instructions from the chairman.
A difficult question that did not arise during the debate at Harvard is this: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Khrushchev, who distinguished himself more through rational behavior during the crisis, but rather an opponent of the type Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could become reality one day.
Today's discussions about limited missile defense and atomic threats from rogue states should be conducted in light of this terrible but certainly realistic thought.
Harvard has launched a new website on the internet where the key documents about the Cuban Crisis as well as current atomic threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org .
